ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">Sources at Glossier tell me that Fleur=E2=80=99s launch wasn=E2=80=99t =
=E2=80=9Cpushed up,=E2=80=9D and that March was
<em>always</em> the target release date. Founder <strong>Emily Weiss</stron=
g> has been focused on fragrance for more than a year, and each of the new =
scents had been in the development pipeline for some time. And yet the rapi=
d-fire rollout of R=C3=AAve and Doux, now followed by Fleur, left neither o=
f them with enough time or marketing support to stand on their own. The cad=
ence feels haphazard, especially from a company that=E2=80=99s always been =
overly precious about <em>everything</em>=E2=80=94custom packaging,
tone, extravagant launches, literal <em>locked</em> mailers that could be o=
pened only at the <em>exact </em>time a code was sent, timed to a million-d=
ollar party, etcetera.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Glossier maintains a =E2=
=80=9Chealthy=E2=80=9D fragrance business at Sephora, according to a person=
 familiar with the matter (overall, Glossier=E2=80=99s fragrance business r=
anks around the 10th spot), but You has also lost considerable momentum in =
the
last year, after debuting on shelves in 2023 as the number one scent at the=
 retailer. =E2=80=9CSales for You core size is down, and that=E2=80=99s bad=
 for a category that=E2=80=99s on fire,=E2=80=9D this person explained. If =
Glossier gets this next launch right, its emerging fragrance portfolio shou=
ld help to =E2=80=9Cbring a halo back to the core and continue to drive gro=
wth to the hero,=E2=80=9D the insider continued. Yes, sure, but additional =
similar-smelling or similarly named S.K.U.s (or =E2=80=9Cflankers=E2=80=9D =
in fragrance industry parlance) could
also cannibalize the hero product. To make it all work, the supporting play=
ers need to grow overall revenue while also bolstering the hero business.</=
p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"=
>Of course, it takes <em>a lot</em> more than Sephora and direct sales to b=
uild a blockbuster perfume business, and despite strong rankings, Glossier =
will need to increase distribution, too. Macy=E2=80=99s, Saks Fifth Avenue,=
 and Neiman Marcus sell the vast majority of prestige
fragrance in the U.S., but <em>none</em> carry Glossier. Meanwhile, fragran=
ce is one of the <em>smallest </em>categories at Sephora=E2=80=93=E2=80=93i=
t drives less than 15 percent of the retailer=E2=80=99s U.S. revenue. =E2=
=80=9CWinning fragrance at Sephora is nice, but if you=E2=80=99re Glossier,=
 you need to win a lot more than fragrance at Sephora,=E2=80=9D said the pe=
rson familiar with Glossier=E2=80=99s business. I have heard that Glossier =
has <em>plans</em> for its fragrance to enter Macy=E2=80=99s, but a source =
told me that although =E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s on the
roadmap,=E2=80=9D a launch isn=E2=80=99t happening yet<em>.</em></p></div>
